Since Henry was born in May, I’ve been having a hard time drawing consistently. When I think about drawing, the idea of deciding what to draw overwhelms me. Which (because I’ve been here before) I know is a sign that I’m rusty, and I just need to draw something — anything — and the next time I sit down, it will be easier. So I started making these little compositions, playing with shape and color. I made a bunch of thumbnail sketches and now when I sit down to draw, instead of hesitating, I can just pick one of these sketches to play with. Happily, once I started doing this, it only took two days before the inspiration came flooding back and I started thinking of other things I wanted to draw. And I’m still having fun with these little compositions. Have you ever felt rusty and afraid to jump back in?

Do you talk yourself out of doing something before you even start? Do you fill your days with the busy (aka easy) work and avoid tackling the big goals? Are you hard on yourself? I know all about this, and am constantly working on getting out of my own way. Lately I find myself repeating over and over in my head “You’re falling behind on your to-do list. You have no time to get anything done.” Well, you know what happens when that’s on a loop in my head? When I do get little bits of time here and there to get something done, I don’t spring into action. Because it feels like why bother, that small amount of time won’t be enough to do much. And it feels like less time than it is, because I keep telling myself I have no time. I’ve been trying this mantra lately: “you have plenty of time.” When I say that, everything feels lighter, more doable. Twenty minutes suddenly does feel like enough to accomplish something. What do you need to do to get out of your own way?

Another composition from the sketches I posted the other day. The idea was to just play with color and shapes as a way of drawing when I wasn’t sure what to draw. When I’ve been away from my drawing practice for a little while, it can be hard to get back into it. Sometimes I feel like my creativity isn’t there anymore. That I’ll never be able to create anything again. And staring at a blank page can be overwhelming. Anyone else?? So I started making these little compositions to draw SOMETHING without overthinking it too much. And it’s working. I’m feeling the creativity coming back. And I can’t wait to share with you what I’ve been making.

Are you ready to get back to making art? I don’t know about you but when I’ve been away from my drawing practice for too long it can be really hard to get back into it. I feel rusty and a little afraid my creativity is gone, which paralyzes me. But I have an idea. Let’s draw together to take the pressure off! You can draw what I’m drawing or draw your own thing. I think Day 2 of Draw with Genna was even better than Day 1! Thank you to those of you that were there live! 
 
Sara said: “My 5 yr old learned how to draw a butterfly using the symmetry tool!” This makes me so happy!!
 
Brie said: “Thank you for sharing your time with us and sparking our collective creativity!” Collective creativity. I love that so much. That's exactly what it was. I felt all of our collective creative energy swirling together. 
 
And remember, if you draw something you don't like or you feel frustrated or overwhelmed, it doesn't mean it was a waste of time. Just the fact that you practiced means you won. And you're not alone.

One day, I got out some crayons to see if my 13-month-old son was interested in drawing with them. He was more interested in chewing on them, but I started doodling. And I kept doodling. And just drew whatever I felt like. Even if that was rainbows over and over and over. And a spark was lit within me. There’s no undo with crayons. There’s no pressure to produce a masterpiece. I felt some of my childlike imagination come back. I felt lighter. It’s been wonderful. I’m hosting a free 3-day live drawing event called Draw with Genna Jan 16-18 so we can all draw and find some lightness together. Comment “DWG” and I’ll DM you the link to save your seat!

And then I found @trutonebulbs . These babies look just like incandescent and it makes me feel like a kid again. (Only the bulbs along the roof are TruTone and the photo doesn’t even do it justice.) Wishing everyone who celebrates a very Merry Christmas!

I’ve had a lot of doubt lately about how I’m spending my time. Am I spending enough quality time with Henry? Am I working enough? Should I be doing x y z more?? But now looking back on the highlights from the last year, I feel really good about what I’ve accomplished and what I’ve experienced. So so grateful.

• I had an idea (Draw with Genna!) and the event was fun and seeing the comments from those who attended and felt inspired and motivated light a fire within me

• Henry learned to crawl and then to walk, and became a toddler in the blink of an eye

• We traveled to Nashville as a family so I could go to the Mark Makers Mastermind retreat, and it turns out, I LOVE line dancing

• I traveled to Charleston alone to attend the fall retreat, leaving Henry alone for 5 days, which was hard but I learned we could both survive it

• 445 of you took my course InDesign Your Portfolio — so many beautiful portfolios were made!

• I finally bought a boat! (A kayak, but it’s a start)

• I discovered a love of crayons and have drawn every single day since July

It wasn’t all sunshine and rainbows, but there sure were a lot of good times this year. Cannot wait to see what 2024 brings.

Surface Designer, Illustrator & Skillshare Top Teacher
